metaclass.name: MetaAttribute
metaclass.description: A metaattribute is a feature within a metaclass that describes a range of values that instances of the metaclass may hold. A metaattribute is a characteristic that describes an object or a link. Examples: The Flow-Type characteristic of a Message allows you to specify whether this Message is information, or a material or financial flow. The Predicate characteristic of the Send link between Message and Org-Unit allows you to specify the condition for sending the Message.

Use rather String with a tabulated values 	Short: S. Use it for small numbers if you compute data. Value must belong to [0-65535] 	Double: H. Use it for numbers if you compute data. Value must belong to [0-18446744073709551616] 	Long: L. Value must belong to [0-4294967295] 	Float: F. Use it for large numbers if you compute data.  	Binary: Q. Internal. properties.name: MetaLayer
properties.description: This parameter indicates if an object belongs to the metamodel layer or to the meta-metamodel layer of the MOF (Meta Object facility) architecture.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert.The MEGA Software environment is based on a four-layer architecture as standardized by the OMG:- M0: The information layer comprises data of the  real world  which the user describes using MEGA products. (e.g.  Alan Smith )- M1: The model layer comprises models that describe data in the information layer. Since MEGA software is a true modeling environment, we can say that this is the  MEGA world  (e.g.  Sales Director )- M2: The metamodel layer comprises several domain-specific metamodels. A metamodel is an  abstract language  defined to write models. A set of concepts relating to the domain being modeled. MEGA products provide an extensive collection of such metamodels, for example the UML metamodel, the workflow (BPMN) metamodel and the business process metamodel. These metamodels can be modified or extended to suit specific requirements.  Metamodel  is the default value and should be used for extensions. (e.g.  Org-Unit )- M3: The meta-metamodel layer comprises the  top level  metamodel required to describe any type of metamodel. The MEGA meta-metamodel complies with the MOF (Meta Object Facility) recommendations of the OMG. It is reflexive, i.e. able to define itself as well as any type of metamodel. MOF is a very high level standardized metamodel, modification of which we do not recommend. Conventionally, meta-meta-objects are prefixed  Meta . (e.g.  MetaClass )

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationAndUserLocationDiagram_TAULD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application and User Location Diagram - TOGAF Application and User Location DiagramThe Application and User Location diagram shows the geographical distribution of applications.It can be used to show where applications are used by the end user; the distribution of where the host application is executed and or delivered in thin client scenarios; the distribution of where applications are developed, tested, and released; etc.Analysis can reveal opportunities for rationalization, as well as duplication and or gaps.The purpose of this diagram is to clearly depict the business locations from which business users typically interact with the applications, but also the hosting location of the application infrastr ucture.The diagram enables:- Identification of the number of package instances needed to sufficiently support the user population that may be spread out geographically- Estimation of the number and the type of user licenses for the package or other software- Estimation of the level of support needed for the users and location of support center- Selection of system management tools, structure, and management system required to support the enterprise users customers partners both locally and remotely- Appropriate planning for the technological components of the business, namely server sizing and network bandwidth, etc.- Performance considerations while implementing application and technology architecture solutionsUsers typically interact with applications in a variety of ways; for example:- To support the operations of the business day-to-day- To participate in the execution of a business process- To access information (look-up, read)- To develop the application- To administer and maintain the application

enumValues.name: Micro_ServiceStructureDiagram_MicroServStructDiag

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataMigrationDiagram_TDMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Migration Diagram - TOGAF Data Migration DiagramData migration is critical when implementing a package or packaged service-based solution.This is particularly true when an existing legacy application is replaced with a package or an enterprise is to be migrated to a larger packages packaged services footprint. Packages tend to have their own data model and during data migration the legacy application data may need to be transformed pr ior to loading into the package.Data migration activities will usually involve the following steps:Extract data from source applications (baseline systems)- Profile source data- Perform data transformation operations, including data quality processes:  - Standardize, normalize, de-duplicate source data (data cleansing)  - Match, merge, and consolidate data from different source(s)  - Source-to-target mappings- Load into target applications (target systems)The purpose of the Data Migration diagram is to show the flow of data from the source to the target applications. The diagram will provide a visual representation of the spread of sources targets and serve as a tool for data auditing and establishing traceability. This diagram can be elaborated or enhanced as detailed as necessary. properties.name: ExecutionOptions
properties.description: Disable MEGA Globals This directive deactivates access to all implicit objects and can therefore be used when we wish to ensure that the script will operate identically from the MEGA script editor or from outside MEGA. Restricted MEGA Globals This directive deactivates access to the MegaDB implicit object. It is highly recommended for implementation of repository extension macros. Full MEGA Globals This directive activate access to all implicit objects and indicates that the script should be used only from the MEGA desktop application.

enumValues.name: Multithread

enumValues.name: JavaLocalNative
enumValues.description: Java Local Native - _ExecutionOptions-Java-LocalNativeFor Java macros.Define the fact that the Native Mega Objects (MegaCOMObject) used in a public Macro function are released when the function ends.MegaCOMObject must be kept to be maintained alive (for example as a member of the Macro). In This case the kept object must be explicitely released when they are no more used, otherwise it leads to a memory leak. To ensure a consistent behavior, such a Macro must inherit from MegaMacro class and keep its members with MegaMacro.KeepMacroMember function.

enumValues.name: JavaCompatibleNative
enumValues.description: Java Compatible Native - _ExecutionOptions-Java-CompatibleNativeFor Java Macros.Explicitly indicates that the macro doesn t work with the LocalNative Mode.Such a macro may cause non lethal (but visible) issues in the Mega Memory management.

metaclass.name: Application
metaclass.description: An application is a software component that can be deployed and provides users with a set of functionalities.

properties.name: Name
properties.description: Short Name of the object (posibility to get the long name with an argument)

properties.name: ApplicationCode
properties.description: The code is a unique mnemonic for your application. This mnemonic should follow the code standards used in your organization.

properties.name: CloudComputing
properties.description: Cloud Computing  defines how the application should be installed1 : On premises  the Appilcation is installed and runs on computers on the premises (in the building) the compagny2 : Infrastructure as a Service (IAAS): Application is installed and runs on an external provider infrastructure (physical or virtual machines and other additional resources such as images in a virtual-machine image-library, raw (block) and file-based storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles)3 : Platform as a Service (PAAS): Application is installed and runs on an external provider computing platform including operating system, programming language execution environment, database, and web server. Internal external developers can develop and run their software solutions on a cloud platform4 : Software as a Service (SAAS): Application is designed, installed and runs by an external delivery partner. Some customization can be implemented during the design phase

properties.name: VersionNumber
properties.description: Indicates the current version number of the application.

properties.name: RequiredMemorySize
properties.description: Indicates the memory required for execution of the application.

properties.name: Prefix
properties.description: Prefix  put at the beginning of the name of the objects generated from an application, a database, etc.

properties.name: ApplicationStereotype
properties.description: In a n-tiers architecture,  this attribute clarify the tier implemented by the application

enumValues.name: PresentationLogic

enumValues.name: BusinessLogic
enumValues.description: Business logic - Application Stereotype-3Tier in charge of business treatments

enumValues.name: DataManagement
enumValues.description: Data management - Application Stereotype-4Tier in charge of data access

properties.name: ApplicationType
properties.description: Specifies if the application is a software package, a specific development, system software (Windows NT, etc.), middleware software or office automation software (Word, Excel, etc.).

properties.name: CurrentState
properties.description: This attribute give the current state of the object in its object live.

properties.name: GlobalExpense
properties.description: aggregation of costs of Applications + Deployment of Application for the current year

properties.name: CurrentNumberOfUsers
properties.description: Sum of the numbers of users specified on all deployment context that are in production today.

properties.name: CostPerUser
properties.description: Calculate the cost per user (aggregation of costs of Applications + Deployment of Application divided by all users specified on deployment context).

properties.name: RankAPM
properties.description: The Rank summarizes the evaluation criteria of the applicaction: the technical efficiency, the functional support and business value. If the sum of the evaluation criteria gives: 3 or 4 the Rank is 1 star5 or 6 the Rank is 2 stars 7 or 8 the Rank is 3 stars 9 or 10 the Rank is 4 stars 11 or 12 the Rank is 5 stars If the sum is less than 3 the application is ranked 0 stars.

properties.name: TechnologyCompliance
properties.description: Technological compliance is calculated as follows:If all technologies used by the application have as enterprise Standard the value  Recommended , technology Compliance takes the value  Recommended .If one of the technologies used by the application has as enterprise Standard the value  Prohibited , technology Compliance takes the value  Prohibited .If at least one of the technologies used by the application has as enterprise Standard the value  Accepted  ,technology Compliance takes the value  Accepted . If the application does not use any technology, or if all technologies used by the application have as enterprise Standard the value  Unknown , technology Compliance takes the value  Unknown .

properties.name: Expenses
properties.description: This present the total expense of the object for the current year from the 1st of january to the 31st of december

properties.name: CapitalExpenses
properties.description: This present the capital expense of the object for the current year from the 1st of january to the 31st of december

properties.name: OperatingExpenses

properties.name: SoftwareResiliencyScoreCASTHighligh
properties.description: Express in %.Software Resiliency indicates programming best practices that make software bullet-proof, more robust and secure. This index is derived through technology-specific code analysis that searches for the presence of code patterns and bad programming practices that may comprise the reliability of the software at short term. Higher is the Software Resiliency, lower is the likelihood of defects occurring in production.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareResiliency
properties.description: Thresholds used for Software Resiliency:High (green): value >= 71.0 Medium (orange): value >= 57.0 Low (red): value < 57.0Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareAgilityScore
properties.description: Express in %.Software Agility indicates the easiness of a development team to understand and maintain an application. This index is derived through technology-specific code analysis that searches for the presence of embedded documentation and code readability good practices.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareAgility
properties.description: Thresholds used for Software Agility categories:High (green): value >= 78.0Medium (orange): value >= 51.0Low (red): value < 51.0Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareEleganceScoreCASTHighligh
properties.description: Express in %.Software Elegance measures the ability to deliver software value with less code complexity. A low Software Elegance score indicates decreased quality in the code resulting in higher defects that become costly to fix at mid-term.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: SoftwareEleganceThresholds
properties.description: Thresholds used for Software Elegance categories:High (green): value >= 88.0Medium (orange): value >= 66.0Low (red): value < 66.0Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: CloudReadyScoreCASTHighlight
properties.description: Express in %. Formula use the survey point reference and applay loss and gain points from the source code scan.

properties.name: CloudReadyScanCASTHighlight
properties.description: Express in %.

properties.name: TechnicalDebtCast
properties.description: Technical Debt measures the effort required to fix coding and architectural violations that remain in the code when an application is released.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: NumberOfLinesOfCodeCast
properties.description: Number of Lines of Code scanned by Cast Highlight for the application.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: NumberOfFilesCast
properties.description: Number of Files scanned by Cast Highlight for the application.Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: AggregationTypeAPM
properties.description: The Cost Aggregation Type explains if the cost of an application is counted in the Global Costs of Applications, or if the cost of this application is divided in the applications systems using the component.

properties.name: BackFiredFunctionPointsCASTHighlight
properties.description: Back-Fired Function Points (BFP) estimate the number of function points of an application. This code-derived metric is based on the lines of code, weighted by an abacus for a given technology. The abacus is taken from QSM <http:  www.qsm.com resources function-point-languages-table> (Quantitative Software Management).Metric powered by CAST Highlight

properties.name: RecoveryPointObjectiveRPO
properties.description: The Recovery Point Objective (RPO) determines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time.Four levels of RPO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable data loss is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable data loss is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable data loss is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable data loss is days)

properties.name: RecoveryTimeObjectiveRTO
properties.description: The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online. This covers, for example, restore data from back-up or fix of a failure.Four levels of RTO need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time needed to bring all critical systems back online is days)

properties.name: WorkRecoveryTimeWRT
properties.description: The Work Recovery Time (WRT) determines the maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity. This could be, for example, checking the databases and logs, making sure the applications or services are running and are available.Four levels of WRT need to be specified:- Critical (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is seconds)- Serious (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is minutes)- Significant (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is hours)- Minor (maximum tolerable amount of time that is needed to verify the system and or data integrity is days)

properties.name: MaximumTolerableDowntimeMTD
properties.description: Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) determines the maximum time a business can tolerate the absence or unavailability of a particular application.Downtime consists of two elements, the Recovery Time Objective and the Work Recovery Time: MTD = RTO + WRTMTD level will be calculated automatically according to RTO and WRT levels, it cannot be modified manually.-	Critical (maximum tolerable downtime is seconds)-	Serious (maximum tolerable downtime is minutes)-	Significant (maximum tolerable downtime is hours)-	Minor (maximum tolerable downtime is days)

properties.name: SLALevel
properties.description: Service-level Agreement (SLA) is a contract between a service provider and its internal or external customers that documents what services the provider will furnish, to calculate the SLA, HOPEX users (Portfolio Manager, Application Owner) will need to fill information on:- Recovery point objective (RPO)- Recovery time objective (RTO)- Work Recovery Time (WRT)- Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD)Then a SLA value will be proposed by HOPEX, if the result is not in line with user expectation, he will be able to change the SLA value manually.
